chnology is likely to become harder and harder. The physicists working on the Manhattan Project understood the implications of their work, but Mark Zuckerberg \"],[0,[5],1,\"still seems blind\"],[0,[],0,\" to the real-world implications of his.\"]]],[10,0],[1,\"p\",[[0,[],0,\"Here are a few broad areas we should focus on going forward:\"]]],[1,\"p\",[[0,[6],1,\"Art\"],[0,[],0,\" is a critical antidote to the excesses of technology. I think \"],[0,[7],1,\"Black Mirror\"],[0,[],0,\" has done more than anything else recently to open the world\'s eyes to the possibility of human frailty to cause deeply disturbing technology futures. We need more art of all kinds — music, literature, television, film, sculpture, poetry — to remind us of our human fallibility and open our eyes to the possibility for unintended consequences.\"]]],[1,\"p\",[[0,[6],1,\"Technology Ethics\"],[0,[],0,\" needs to become more sophisticated, and we need mechanisms to bake in better incentives to our technology system. No doubt our social media ecosystem would be \"],[0,[8],1,\"far healthier\"],[0,[],0,\" if it weren\'t heavily incentivized to maximize time-on-site to serve ads. Governments are struggling to solve this problem with existing social-media giants, but in some sense it\'s too late. We should have baked better incentives into the structure of our technologies from the beginning.\"]]],[1,\"p\",[[0,[6],1,\"Tech-forward government\"],[0,[],0,\" is critical for avoiding perverse incentives on the next tech frontier. Why is there not a government agency in Washington focused on these issues, and staffed with highly competent technologists? Instead, the only tech-forward parts of our government are the organizations like the NSA that are tasked with \"],[0,[9],1,\"stealing the citizens\'s private information\"],[0,[],0,\".\"]]],[1,\"p\",[[0,[6],1,\"Philosophy\"],[0,[],0,\" is critical in these challenging times. The maturity of our thinking around technology will always be a function of the maturity of the individuals involved. We need to foster a culture of intellectual maturity, that draws on \"],[0,[10],1,\"ancient\"],[0,[],0,\" \"],[0,[11],1,\"wisdom\"],[0,[],0,\" rather than thin and immature hedonistic \\\"follow your bliss\\\" mindsets. I\'m heartened by the fact that Twitter\'s CEO Jack Dorsey \"],[0,[12],1,\"spends weeks at a time in silent meditation\"],[0,[],0,\". I\'m glad deep thinkers like \"],[0,[13],1,\"Sam Harris\"],[0,[],0,\" and \"],[0,[14],1,\"Tristan Harris\"],[0,[],0,\" are popular among the tech crowd. More of this.\"]]],[10,1],[1,\"p\",[[0,[],0,\"None of this is easy, but we must keep negotiating this problem before it\'s too late. Let\'s become more clear-eyed about human frailty and our increasing power of destruction. Let\'s stop using the term \\\"disruption\\\" in the tech community as if it\'s an obvious force for good. Let\'s each look inward and integrate our own \"],[0,[15],1,\"potential for destruction\"],[0,[],0,\" \"],[0,[6],1,\"before\"],[0,[],0,\" we invent the most powerful technologies in human history.\"]]]]}',1594597109302,'2020-07-12 23:38:29'),('5f0b9f0b76e291001ef8b0c8','5f0b9f0a76e291001ef8b0c6','{\"version\":\"0.3.1\",\"markups\":[],\"atoms\":[],\"cards\":[],\"sections\":[[1,\"p\",[[0,[],0,\"\"]]]]}',1594597130994,'2020-07-12 23:38:51'),('5f0b9f1176e291001ef8b0ca','5f0b9f0a76e291001ef8b0c6','{\"version\":\"0.3.1\",\"atoms\":[[\"soft-return\",\"\",{}]],\"cards\":[],\"markups\":[[\"em\"],[\"a\",[\"href\",\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stoicism\"]],[\"strong\"]],\"sections\":[[1,\"p\",[[0,[0],1,\"An experiment in community, philosophy and self-improvement\"]]],[1,\"p\",[[0,[],0,\"We’re living in a time of disconnection and isolation. And on top of that, powerful forces like Twitter\'s character limit and the 24-hour news cycle mean that our culture is often incredibly shallow — our conversations on important issues often lack emotional and intellectual depth.\"]]],[1,\"p\",[[0,[1],1,\"Stoic philosophy\"],[0,[