INSERT INTO `posts` VALUES ('5f0b9dd376e291001ef8b09e','892f4ce2-c6d7-4c94-a548-7e5b96202c53','Sensatez — a mental scaffold','sensatez-a-mental-scaffold-2','{\"version\":\"0.3.1\",\"atoms\":[],\"cards\":[],\"markups\":[[\"em\"]],\"sections\":[[1,\"p\",[[0,[],0,\"A lot of disparate ideas pass through my head on a daily basis. They\'re chaotic, which is giving me a somewhat murky mind.\"]]],[1,\"p\",[[0,[],0,\"I\'ve tried freeform journaling in the past, each page a raw stream of consciousness filled with random drawings and doodles and private desires. Right now I\'m seeking something more structured to gather my thoughts — hence this new blog. A key ingredient for me right now is that these posts will be public, which will be a forcing function for me to think properly before hitting \"],[0,[0],1,\"publish\"],[0,[],0,\", so that this blog is a more structured record of my thoughts about the world.\"]]],[1,\"p\",[[0,[],0,\"I plan to cover a broad range of topics. For now, the name of the blog is \"],[0,[0],1,\"Sensatez\"],[0,[],0,\", a Spanish word meaning \"],[0,[0],1,\"sanity and sensibility\"],[0,[],0,\". I\'ll be writing about politics, philosophy, science, technology, music, ethics, and other topics on my mind. Over time, I may find a groove and narrow the blog\'s focus somewhat, but for now, \"],[0,[0],1,\"Sensatez\"],[0,[],0,\" is a broad mental scaffold to keep my disparate musings from clouding my head.\"]]]]}','<p>A lot of disparate ideas pass through my head on a daily basis. They\'re chaotic, which is giving me a somewhat murky mind.</p><p>I\'ve tried freeform journaling in the past, each page a raw stream of consciousness filled with random drawings and doodles and private desires. Right now I\'m seeking something more structured to gather my thoughts — hence this new blog. A key ingredient for me right now is that these posts will be public, which will be a forcing function for me to think properly before hitting <em>publish</em>, so that this blog is a more structured record of my thoughts about the world.</p><p>I plan to cover a broad range of topics. For now, the name of the blog is <em>Sensatez</em>, a Spanish word meaning <em>sanity and sensibility</em>. I\'ll be writing about politics, philosophy, science, technology, music, ethics, and other topics on my mind. Over time, I may find a groove and narrow the blog\'s focus somewhat, but for now, <em>Sensatez</em> is a broad mental scaffold to keep my disparate musings from clouding my head.</p>','5f0b9dd376e291001ef8b09e','A lot of disparate ideas pass through my head on a daily basis. They\'re chaotic,\nwhich is giving me a somewhat murky mind.\n\nI\'ve tried freeform journaling in the past, each page a raw stream of\nconsciousness filled with random drawings and doodles and private desires. Right\nnow I\'m seeking something more structured to gather my thoughts — hence this new\nblog. A key ingredient for me right now is that these posts will be public,\nwhich will be a forcing function for me to think properly before hitting publish\n, so that this blog is a more structured record of my thoughts about the world.\n\nI plan to cover a broad range of topics. For now, the name of the blog is \nSensatez, a Spanish word meaning sanity and sensibility. I\'ll be writing about\npolitics, philosophy, science, technology, music, ethics, and other topics on my\nmind. Over time, I may find a groove and narrow the blog\'s focus somewhat, but\nfor now, Sensatez is a broad mental scaffold to keep my disparate musings from\nclouding my head.','https://s3.amazonaws.com/bucketeer-7bce7cd3-3552-4b4e-8681-9def67f16a7f/2020/07/coffee-eagle-l7HysfP9BPU-unsplash.jpg',0,'published',NULL,'public','1','2020-07-12 23:33:39','1','2020-07-15 08:19:54','1','2020-07-05 23:34:00','1',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'post',0),('5f0b9e6276e291001ef8b0a6','c5df6b91-56ce-4e2a-a046-ed73e135b58a','Chopin\'s Nocturnes','chopins-nocturnes','{\"version\":\"0.3.1\",\"atoms\":[],\"cards\":[],\"markups\":[[\"a\",[\"href\",\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-gDinVAmtA0\"]],[\"em\"],[\"a\",[\"href\",\"https://www.college.columbia.edu/core/content/whitehead-plato\"]],[\"a\",[\"href\",\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philosophi%C3%A6_Naturalis_Principia_Mathematica\"]]],\"sections\":[[1,\"p\",[[0,[0],0,\"Chopin\'s \"],[0,[1],2,\"Nocturnes\"],[0,[],0,\" are perfect, pinnacle human expression.\"]]],[1,\"p\",[[0,[],0,\"Every art form has its peak output, a work so unparalleled in beauty and form that all other practitioners live in its shadow. All philosophy is a \"],[0,[2],1,\"series of footnotes to Plato\"],[0,[],0,\". No great basketball player since Michael Jordan\'s reign has ever escaped the incessant comparisons. And good luck publishing a physics manuscript after Isaas Newton dropped \"],[0,[1,3],2,\"Principia\"],[0,[],0,\" in 1687 and invented calculus and the laws of motion.\"]]],[1,\"p\",[[0,[],0,\"To me, Chopin\'s \"],[0,[1],1,\"Nocturnes\"],[0,[],0,\" are in this god-tier category — a work so emotionally resonant and sublimely human that all subsequent attempts must be seen through its lens. All piano melodies feel derivative by comparison. It\'s like the whole solo-piano repertoire is simply a subset of Chopin\'s expansive genius.\"]]]]}','<p><a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-gDinVAmtA0\">Chopin\'s <em>Nocturnes</em></a> are perfect, pinnacle human expression.</p><p>Every art form has its peak output, a work so unparalleled in beauty and form that all other practitioners live in its shadow. All philosophy is a <a href=\"https://www.college.columbia.edu/core/content/whitehead-plato\">series of footnotes to Plato</a>. No great basketball player since Michael Jordan\'s reign has ever escaped the incessant comparisons. And good luck publishing a physics manuscript after Isaas Newton dropped <em><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philosophi%C3%A6_Naturalis_Principia_Mathematica\">Principia</a></em> in 1687 and invented calculus and the laws of motion.</p><p>To me, Chopin\'s <em>Nocturnes</em> are in this god-tier category — a work so emotionally resonant and sublimely human that all subsequent attempts must be seen through its lens. All piano melodies feel derivative by comparison. It\'s like the whole solo-piano repertoire is simply a subset of Chopin\'s expansive genius.</p>','5f0b9e6276e291001ef8b0a6','Chopin\'s Nocturnes [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-gDinVAmtA0] are perfect,\npinnacle human expression.\n\nEvery art form has its peak output, a work so unparalleled in beauty and form\nthat all other practitioners live in its shadow. All philosophy is a series of\nfootnotes to Plato\n[https://www.college.columbia.edu/core/content/whitehead-plato]. No great\nbasketball player since Michael Jordan\'s reign has ever escaped the incessant\ncomparisons. And good luck publishing a physics manuscript after Isaas Newton\ndropped Principia\n[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philosophi%C3%A6_Naturalis_Principia_Mathematica] \nin 1687 and invented calculus and the laws of motion.\n\nTo me, Chopin\'s Nocturnes are in this god-tier category — a work so emotionally\nresonant and sublimely human that all subsequent attempts must be seen through\nits lens. All piano melodies feel derivative by comparison. It\'s like the whole\nsolo-piano repertoire is simply a subset of Chopin\'s expansive genius.','https://s3.amazonaws.com/bucketeer-7bce7cd3-3552-4b4e-8681-9def67f16a7f/2020/07/ryan-holloway-35ZPwMahrOY-unsplash.jpg',0,'published',NULL,'public','1','2020-07-12 23:36:02','1','2020-07-15 08:19:50','1','2020-07-05 23:37:00','1',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'post',0),('5f0b9eb776e291001ef8b0ae','8bccfcf7-3b0d-49ac-9040-6fd0091f72ed','Fonts for sheet music?','fonts-for-sheet-music','{\"version\":\"0.3.1\",\"atoms\":[],\"cards\":[],\"markups\":[[\"a\",[\"href\",\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Font\"]],[\"a\",[\"href\",\"https://musescore.org/\"]]],\"sections\":[[1,\"p\",[[0,[],0,\"Why is there not an equivalent of \"],[0,[0],1,\"typographical fonts\"],[0,[],0,\" for sheet music? Different sheet books and score sites print musical staff notation in subtly different ways, but there\'s a surprisingly small amount of variability. Where are the legibility tweaks, the creative interpretations, the artistic flare?\"]]],[1,\"p\",[[0,[],0,\"Certainly words are more varied and versatile, more omnipresent in our daily experience, than the treble and bass clef. And the process of expressing written music through an instrument is much more of a technical exercise in timing and precision than simply reading. But the sheer lack of flare and variability in musical notation is still somewhat surprising. Different fonts have different legibility characteristics, invoke wildly different aesthetic feelings, and speak volumes about the presenter\'s intent. If musical notation were renderable in a similarly broad array of forms, I\'m sure musical subcultures would form preferences for different styles, and musical expression would become that much richer and more interesting.\"]]],[1,\"p\",[[0,[],0,\"For what it\'s worth, I personally fine \"],[0,[1],1,\"MuseScore\'s\"],[0,[],0,\" staff notation on the printed page to be subtly superior to other styles I\'ve seen, for it\'s legibility and clarity. But I wish there were a richer vocabulary and broader variability around these style differences in musical notation, just like we have for letters and numbers.\"]]]]}','<p>Why is there not an equivalent of <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Font\">typographical fonts</a> for sheet music? Different sheet books and score sites print musical staff notation in subtly different ways, but there\'s a surprisingly small amount of variability. Where are the legibility tweaks, the creative interpretations, the artistic flare?</p><p>Certainly words are more varied and versatile, more omnipresent in our daily experience, than the treble and bass clef. And the process of expressing written music through an instrument is much more of a technical exercise in timing and precision than simply reading. But the sheer lack of flare and variability in musical notation is still somewhat surprising. Different fonts have different legibility characteristics, invoke wildly different aesthetic feelings, and speak volumes about the presenter\'s intent. If musical notation were renderable in a similarly broad array of forms, I\'m sure musical subcultures would form preferences for different styles, and musical expression would become that much richer and more interesting.</p><p>For what it\'s worth, I personally fine <a href=\"https://musescore.org/\">MuseScore\'s</a> staff notation on the printed page to be subtly superior to other styles I\'ve seen, for it\'s legibility and clarity. But I wish there were a richer vocabulary and broader variability around these style differences in musical notation, just like we have for letters and numbers.</p>','5f0b9eb776e291001ef8b0ae','Why is there not an equivalent of typographical fonts\n[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Font] for sheet music? Different sheet books and\nscore sites print musical staff notation in subtly different ways, but there\'s a\nsurprisingly small amount of variability. Where are the legibility tweaks, the\ncreative interpretations, the artistic flare?\n\nCertainly words are more varied and versatile, more omnipresent in our daily\nexperience, than the treble and bass clef. And the process of expressing written\nmusic through an instrument is much more of a technical exercise in timing and\nprecision than simply reading. But the sheer lack of flare and variability in\nmusical notation is still somewhat surprising. Different fonts have different\nlegibility characteristics, invoke wildly different aesthetic feelings, and\nspeak volumes about the presenter\'s intent. If musical notation were renderable\nin a similarly broad array of forms, I\'m sure musical subcultures would form\npreferences for different styles, and musical expression would become that much\nricher and more interesting.\n\nFor what it\'s worth, I personally fine MuseScore\'s [https://musescore.org/] \nstaff notation on the printed page to be subtly superior to other styles I\'ve\nseen, for it\'s legibility and clarity. But I wish there were a richer vocabulary\nand broader variability around these style differences in musical notation, just\nlike we have for letters and numbers.','https://s3.amazonaws.com/bucketeer-7bce7cd3-3552-4b4e-8681-9def67f16a7f/2020/07/fonts-1.jpg',0,'published',NULL,'public','1','2020-07-12 23:37:27','1','2020-07-15 08:19:41','1','2020-07-06 23:37:00','1',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'post',0),('5f0b9ece76e291001ef8b0b6','cf29fe8b-922e-41d5-8aff-7bb42a7740f1','In defense of a boring president','in-defense-of-a-boring-president','{\"version\":\"0.3.1\",\"atoms\":[],\"cards\":[],\"markups\":[[\"strong\"]],\"sections\":[[1,\"p\",[[0,[],0,\"Almost everyone I know, myself included, will support Joe Biden in November with a bit of regret. It feels like electing a septuagenarian who\'s been in government since the actual 70\'s is a bit of a missed opportunity.\"]]],[1,\"p\",[[0,[],0,\"But goddamn if I will not do everything I can to get this man in power. I don\'t think our country can survive another four years of orange terror. It\'s truly an existential election, and I don\'t say that lightly.\"]]],[1,\"p\",[[0,[],0,\"I\'m tired of having to care what\'s happening on Twitter. I\'m tired of knowing that US Foreign Policy could do a 180° shift and gear up for war, all because one man got triggered. I\'m tired of feeling like I have to be paying attention every day.\"]]],[1,\"p\",[[0,[],0,\"I for one can\'t wait to have a president I don\'t think about for weeks at a time. I\'m deeply looking forward to having a boring president. Let\'s embrace \"],[0,[0],1,\"Boring Biden\"],[0,[],0,\" and all do everything we can to get him elected!\"]]]]}','<p>Almost everyone I know, myself included, will support Joe Biden in November with a bit of regret. It feels like electing a septuagenarian who\'s been in government since the actual 70\'s is a bit of a missed opportunity.</p><p>But goddamn if I will not do everything I can to get this man in power. I don\'t think our country can survive another four years of orange terror. It\'s truly an existential election, and I don\'t say that lightly.</p><p>I\'m tired of having to care what\'s happening on Twitter. I\'m tired of knowing that US Foreign Policy could do a 180° shift and gear up for war, all because one man got triggered. I\'m tired of feeling like I have to be paying attention every day.</p><p>I for one can\'t wait to have a president I don\'t think about for weeks at a time. I\'m deeply looking forward to having a boring president. Let\'s embrace <strong>Boring Biden</strong> and all do everything we can to get him elected!</p>','5f0b9ece76e291001ef8b0b6','Almost everyone I know, myself included, will support Joe Biden in November with\na bit of regret. It feels like electing a septuagenarian who\'s been in\ngovernment since the actual 70\'s is a bit of a missed opportunity.\n\nBut goddamn if I will not do everything I can to get this man in power. I don\'t\nthink our country can survive another four years of orange terror. It\'s truly an\nexistential election, and I don\'t say that lightly.\n\nI\'m tired of having to care what\'s happening on Twitter. I\'m tired of knowing\nthat US Foreign Policy could do a 180° shift and gear up for war, all because\none man got triggered. I\'m tired of feeling like I have to be paying attention\nevery day.\n\nI for one can\'t wait to have a president I don\'t think about for weeks at a\ntime. I\'m deeply looking forward to having a boring president. Let\'s embrace \nBoring Biden and all do everything we can to get him elected!','https://s3.amazonaws.com/bucketeer-7bce7cd3-3552-4b4e-8681-9def67f16a7f/2020/07/Screen-Shot-2020-07-10-at-11.35.16-AM.png',0,'published',NULL,'public','1','2020-07-12 23:37:50','1','2020