e mental health of our society. We\'re 15 years into this social media experiment, and it\'s \"],[0,[0],1,\"not\"],[0,[],0,\" \"],[0,[1],1,\"going\"],[0,[],0,\" \"],[0,[2],1,\"particularly\"],[0,[],0,\" \"],[0,[3],1,\"well\"],[0,[],0,\", is it?\"]]],[1,\"p\",[[0,[],0,\"\"],[0,[],0,\"The deep divisions and disruptions caused by social media should be a learning opportunity for the tech community, to reassess some of their core principles. We need to wrestle with this question:\"]]],[1,\"blockquote\",[[0,[],0,\"Looking forward, how do we avoid such a massive mistake from happening again in the next society-shifting technology innovation — be it Virtual Reality, Bioengineering, Weaponized Drones, or Artificial Intelligence?\"]]],[1,\"p\",[[0,[],0,\"I don\'t think anyone knows the answers to this question yet, but we know getting it right is of critical importance. The next technology dystopia could be far worse than social media — be it an engineered \"],[0,[4],1,\"pandemic 100x more deadly than COVID-19\"],[0,[],0,\", or an AI that decides its creator species is more of a nuisance than an aid to its ultimate goals.\"]]],[1,\"p\",[[0,[],0,\"Avoiding dystopian outcomes with each successive wave of new technology is likely to become harder and harder. The physicists working on the Manhattan Project understood the dark implications of their work, but Mark Zuckerberg still seems unwilling to grapple with the real-world consequences of his.\"]]],[10,0],[1,\"p\",[[0,[],0,\"Here are a few broad areas we should focus on going forward:\"]]],[1,\"p\",[[0,[5],1,\"Art\"],[0,[],0,\" is a critical antidote to the excesses of technology. I think \"],[0,[6],1,\"Black Mirror\"],[0,[],0,\" has done more than anything else recently to open the world\'s eyes to the possibility of human frailty to cause deeply disturbing technology futures. We need more art of all kinds — music, literature, television, film, sculpture, poetry — to remind us of our human fallibility and open our eyes to the possibility for unintended consequences.\"]]],[1,\"p\",[[0,[5],1,\"Technology Ethics\"],[0,[],0,\" needs to become more sophisticated, and we need mechanisms to bake in better incentives to our technology system. No doubt our social media ecosystem would be \"],[0,[7],1,\"far healthier\"],[0,[],0,\" if it weren\'t heavily incentivized to maximize time-on-site to serve ads. Governments are struggling to solve this problem with existing social-media giants, but in some sense it\'s too late. We should have baked better incentives into the structure of our technologies from the beginning.\"]]],[1,\"p\",[[0,[5],1,\"Tech-forward government\"],[0,[],0,\" is critical for avoiding perverse incentives on the next tech frontier. Why is there not a government agency in Washington focused on these issues, and staffed with highly competent technologists? Instead, the only tech-forward parts of our government are the organizations like the NSA that are tasked with \"],[0,[8],1,\"stealing the citizens\'s private information\"],[0,[],0,\".\"]]],[1,\"p\",[[0,[5],1,\"Philosophy\"],[0,[],0,\" is critical in these challenging times. The maturity of our thinking around technology will always be a function of the maturity of the individuals involved. We need to foster a culture of intellectual maturity, that draws on \"],[0,[9],1,\"ancient\"],[0,[],0,\" \"],[0,[10],1,\"wisdom\"],[0,[],0,\" rather than thin and immature hedonistic \\\"follow your bliss\\\" mindsets. I\'m heartened by the fact that Twitter\'s CEO Jack Dorsey \"],[0,[11],1,\"spends weeks at a time in silent meditation\"],[0,[],0,\". I\'m glad deep thinkers like \"],[0,[12],1,\"Sam Harris\"],[0,[],0,\" and \"],[0,[13],1,\"Tristan Harris\"],[0,[],0,\" are popular among the tech crowd. More of this.\"]]],[10,1],[1,\"p\",[[0,[],0,\"None of this is easy, but we must keep negotiating this problem before it\'s too late. Let\'s become more clear-eyed about human frailty and our increasing power of destruction. Let\'s stop using the term \\\"disruption\\\" in the tech community as if it\'s an obvious force for good. Let\'s each look inward and integrate our own \"],[0,[14],1,\"potential for destruction\"],[0,[],0,\" \"],[0,[5],1,\"before\"],[0,[],0,\" we invent the most powerful technologies in human history.\"]]]]}','<p>I think in 30 years we\'ll look back at the founding of Facebook the way we look back at the first McDonald\'s — a technology-gone-wrong tale of good intentions and bad incentives causing a deeply addictive health epidemic.</p><p>It\'s now well-understood that Twitter, Facebook and Instagram have caused massive problems not just for the health of our political systems, but also for the mental health of our society. We\'re 15 years into this social media experiment, and it\'s <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Presidency_of_Donald_Trump\">not</a> <a href=\"https://www.cnn.com/2019/05/17/health/suicide-rates-young-girls-study/index.html\">going</a> <a href=\"https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2019/12/social-media-democracy/600763/\">particularly</a> <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fear_of_missing_out\">well</a>, is it?</p><p>The deep divisions and disruptions caused by social media should be a learning opportunity for the tech community, to reassess some of their core principles. We need to wrestle with this question:</p><blockquote>Looking forward, how do we avoid such a massive mistake from happening again in the next society-shifting technology innovation — be it Virtual Reality, Bioengineering, Weaponized Drones, or Artificial Intelligence?</blockquote><p>I don\'t think anyone knows the answers to this question yet, but we know getting it right is of critical importance. The next technology dystopia could be far worse than social media — be it an engineered <a href=\"https://www.nature.com/scitable/blog/viruses101/avian/#:~:text=The%20uncensored%20study%20by%20Fouchier,once%20in%20naturally%20occurring%20H5N1.\">pandemic 100x more deadly than COVID-19</a>, or an AI that decides its creator species is more of a nuisance than an aid to its ultimate goals.</p><p>Avoiding dystopian outcomes with each successive wave of new technology is likely to become harder and harder. The physicists working on the Manhattan Project understood the dark implications of their work, but Mark Zuckerberg still seems unwilling to grapple with the real-world consequences of his.</p><hr><p>Here are a few broad areas we should focus on going forward:</p><p><strong>Art</strong> is a critical antidote to the excesses of technology. I think <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metalhead_(Black_Mirror)\">Black Mirror</a> has done more than anything else recently to open the world\'s eyes to the possibility of human frailty to cause deeply disturbing technology futures. We need more art of all kinds — music, literature, television, film, sculpture, poetry — to remind us of our human fallibility and open our eyes to the possibility for unintended consequences.</p><p><strong>Technology Ethics</strong> needs to become more sophisticated, and we need mechanisms to bake in better incentives to our technology system. No doubt our social media ecosystem would be <a href=\"https://humanetech.com/\">far healthier</a> if it weren\'t heavily incentivized to maximize time-on-site to serve ads. Governments are struggling to solve this problem with existing social-media giants, but in some sense it\'s too late. We should have baked better incentives into the structure of our technologies from the beginning.</p><p><strong>Tech-forward government</strong> is critical for avoiding perverse incentives on the next tech frontier. Why is there not a government agency in Washington focused on these issues, and staffed with highly competent technologists? Instead, the only tech-forward parts of our government are the organizations like the NSA that are tasked with <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edward_Snowden\">stealing the citizens\'s private information</a>.</p><p><strong>Philosophy</strong> is critical in these challenging times. The maturity of our thinking around technology will always be a function of the maturity of the individuals involved. We need to foster a culture of intellectual maturity, that draws on <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stoicism\">ancient</a> <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Buddhism\">wisdom</a> rather than thin and immature hedonistic \"follow your bliss\" mindsets. I\'m heartened by the fact that Twitter\'s CEO Jack Dorsey <a href=\"https://www.firstpost.com/health/twitter-ceo-jack-dorsey-did-silent-vipassana-for-10-days-its-almost-impossible-to-follow-his-schedule-in-everyday-life-7702251.html\">spends weeks at a time in silent meditation</a>. I\'m glad deep thinkers like <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sam_Harris\">Sam Harris</a> and <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tristan_Harris\">Tristan Harris</a> are popular among the tech crowd. More of this.</p><hr><p>None of this is easy, but we must keep negotiating this problem before it\'s too late. Let\'s become more clear-eyed about human frailty and our increasing power of destruction. Let\'s stop using the term \"disruption\" in the tech community as if it\'s an obvious force for good. Let\'s each look inward and integrate our own <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shadow_(psychology)\">potential for destruction</a> <strong>before</strong> we invent the most powerful technologies in human history.</p>','5f0b9eed76e291001ef8b0be','I think in 30 years we\'ll look back at the founding of Facebook the way we look\nback at the first McDonald\'s — a technology-gone-wrong tale of good intentions\nand bad incentives causing a deeply addictive health epidemic.\n\nIt\'s now well-understood that Twitter, Facebook and Instagram have caused\nmassive problems not just for the health of our political systems, but also for\nthe mental health of our society. We\'re 15 years into this social media\nexperiment, and it\'s not\n[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Presidency_of_Donald_Trump] going\n[https://www.cnn.com/2019/05/17/health/suicide-rates-young-girls-study/index.html] \n particularly\n[https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2019/12/social-media-democracy/600763/] \n well [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fear_of_missing_out], is it?\n\nThe deep divisions and disruptions caused by social media should be a learning\nopportunity for the tech community, to reassess some of their core principles.\nWe need to wrestle with this question:\n\n> Looking forward, how do we avoid such a massive mistake from happening again in\nthe next society-shifting technology innovation — be it Virtual Reality,\nBioengineering, Weaponized Drones, or Artificial Intelligence?\nI don\'t think anyone knows the answers to this question yet, but we know getting\nit right is of critical importance. The next technology dystopia could be far\nworse than social media — be it an engineered pandemic 100x more deadly than\nCOVID-19\n[https://www.nature.com/scitable/blog/viruses101/avian/#:~:text=The%20uncensored%20study%20by%20Fouchier,once%20in%20naturally%20occurring%20H5N1.]\n, or an AI that decides its creator species is more of a nuisance than an aid to\nits ultimate goals.\n\nAvoiding dystopian outcomes with each successive wave of new technology is\nlikely to become harder and harder. The physicists working on the Manhattan\nProject understood the dark implications of their work, but Mark Zuckerberg\nstill seems unwilling to grapple with the real-world consequences of his.\n\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n\nHere are a few broad areas we should focus on going forward:\n\nArt is a critical antidote to the excesses of technology. I think Black Mirror\n[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metalhead_(Black_Mirror)] has done more than\nanything else recently to open the world\'s eyes to the possibility of human\nfrailty to cause deeply disturbing technology futures. We need more art of all\nkinds — music, literature, television, film, sculpture, poetry — to remind us of\nour human fallibility and open our eyes to the possibility for unintended\nconsequences.\n\nTechnology Ethics needs to become more sophisticated, and we need mechanisms to\nbake in better incentives to our technology system. No doubt our social media\necosystem would be far healthier [https://humanetech.com/] if it weren\'t heavily\nincentivized to maximize time-on-site to serve ads. Governments are struggling\nto solve this problem with existing social-media giants, but in some sense it\'s\ntoo late. We should have baked better incentives into the structure of our\ntechnologies from the beginning.\n\nTech-forward government is critical for avoiding perverse incentives on the next\ntech frontier. Why is there not a government agency in Washington focused on\nthese issues, and staffed with highly competent technologists? Instead, the only\ntech-forward parts of our government are the organizations like the NSA that are\ntasked with stealing the citizens\'s private information\n[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edward_Snowden].\n\nPhilosophy is critical in these challenging times. The maturity of our thinking\naround technology will always be a function of the maturity of the individuals\ninvolved. We need to foster a culture of intellectual maturity, that draws on \nancient [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stoicism] wisdom\n[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Buddhism] rather than thin and immature\nhedonistic \"follow your bliss\" mindsets. I\'m heartened by the fact that\nTwitter\'s CEO Jack Dorsey spends weeks at a time in silent meditation\n[https://www.firstpost.com/health/twitter-ceo-jack-dorsey-did-silent-vipassana-for-10-days-its-almost-impossible-to-follow-his-schedule-in-everyday-life-7702251.html]\n. I\'m glad deep thinkers like Sam Harris\n[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sam_Harris] and Tristan Harris\n[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tristan_Harris] are popular among the tech crowd.\nMore of this.\n\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n\nNone of this is easy, but we must keep negotiating this problem before it\'s too\nlate. Let\'s become more clear-eyed about human frailty and our increasing power\nof destruction. Let\'s stop using the term \"disruption\" in the tech community as\nif it\'s an obvious force for good. Let\'s each look inward and integrate our own \npotential for destruction [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shadow_(psychology)] \nbefore we invent the most powerful technologies in human history.','https://s3.amazonaws.com/bucketeer-7bce7cd3-3552-4b4e-8681-9def67f16a7f/2020/07/restaurant-McDonalds-museum-Ray-Kroc-Illinois-Des--1-.jpg',0,'published',NULL,'public','1','2020-07-12 23:38:21','1','2020-07-16 05:45:03','1','2020-07-10 23:38:00','1',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'post',0),('5f0b9f0a76e291001ef8b0c6','3a4406dd-90ae-4dda-8c90-2d70877476bb','Stoic Circles','stoic-circles','{\"version\":\"0.3.1\",\"atoms\":[[\"soft-return\",\"\",{}]],\"cards\":[],\"markups\":[[\"em\"],[\"a\",[\"href\",\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stoicism\"]],[\"strong\"]],\"sections\":[[1,\"p\",[[0,[0],1,\"An experiment in community, philosophy and self-improvement\"]]],[1,\"p\",[[0,[],0,\"We’re living in a time of disconnection and isolation. And on top of that, powerful forces like Twitter\'s character limit and the 24-hour news cycle mean that our culture is often incredibly shallow — our conversations on important issues often lack emotional and intellectual depth.\"]]],[1,\"p\",[[0,[1],1,\"Stoic philosophy\"],[0,[],0,\" offers a deep, rich and time-tested antidote to these ills.\"]]],[1,\"p\",[[0,[],0,\"A \"],[0,[2],1,\"Stoic Circle\"],[0,[],0,\" is a small intentional community of 6-8 people that meets each week to discuss a single principle from the Stoic philosophers. We seek to apply the lessons of the Stoics into our own lives. Part group therapy, part philosophy discussion, part self-help circle, it’s an intentional community that strives to go beneath the surface to get at the deep emotional issues we face in our lives.\"]]],[1,\"h2\",[[0,[2],1,\"Values inside the Circle\"]]],[1,\"p\",[[0,[],0,\"When we enter the circle each week, we choose to embody the following values:\"]]],[3,\"ul\",[[[0,[2],1,\"Self-improvement\"],[0,[],0,\" — We strive to improve ourselves. We actively encourage this mindset in those around us. We seek to avoid negative or unproductive thought patterns and recognize that growth is a never-ending game.\"]],[[0,[2],1,\"Openness\"],[0,[],0,\" — We value honesty and transparency, and are willing to speak frankly about our own inner lives. We try to look deeply within ourselves in order to recognize, articulate and share our own insecurities, weaknesses and self-doubts, as well as our inner triumphs and victories over fear.\"]]]],[1,\"h2\",[[0,[2],1,\"Format of the Circle\"]]],[1,\"p\",[[0,[],0,\"A Stoic Circle consists of a 1 hour meeting per week for 6 weeks. For now this will be on Zoom to facilitate social distancing.\"]]],[1,\"p\",[[0,[],0,\"Each week we will discuss a single short excerpt from the Stoic philosophers, and a few related prompts to provoke discussion. Here is the six week syllabus:\"]]],[1,\"h3\",[[0,[2],1,\"Week I — Avoiding outrage\"]]],[1,\"blockquote\",[[0,[0],0,\"Choose not to be harmed — and you won’t feel harmed. Don’t feel harmed — and you haven’t been.  \"],[0,[2],2,\"~ Marcus Aurelius\"]]],[3,\"ul\",[[[0,[],0,\"Have you observed any negative impacts in your life from the emotion of outrage?\"]],[[0,[],0,\"Outrage is addictive. What habits or behaviors do you engage in that provoke your outrage? What are some techniques for avoiding this?\"]]]],[1,\"h3\",[[0,[2],1,\"Week II — Self-discipline\"]]],[1,\"blockquote\",[[0,[0],0,\"Be tolerant with others and strict with yourself.  \"],[0,[2],2,\"~ Marcus Aurelius\"]]],[3,\"ul\",[[[0,[],0,\"It\'s easy to look out at the world and cast judgement. Have you found yourself able to resist this urge? If so, have you found this to be beneficial?\"]],[[0,[],0,\"Share a story of a time when you managed to stay disciplined towards a healthy intention you set, and how this improved your life.\"]]]],[1,\"h3\",[[0,[2],1,\"Week III — The value of time\"]]],[1,\"blockquote\",[[0,[0],0,\"People are frugal in guarding their personal property; but as soon as it comes to squandering time they are most wasteful of the one thing in which it is right to be stingy.  \"],[0,[2],2,\"~ Seneca\"]]],[3,\"ul\",[[[0,[],0,\"Are there areas of your life you\'re spending more time on than you think ideal? Do you suffer from any addictions or compulsions that eat away at your time but that you\'re unable to abstain from?\"]],[[0,[],0,\"What approaches do you have for evaluating whether different activities are worth your time?\"]]]],[1,\"h3\",[[0,[2],1,\"Week IV — Facing mortality\"]]],[1,\"blockquote\",[[0,[0],0,\"You could leave life right now. Let that determine what you do and say and think.  \"],[0,[2],2,\"~ Marcus Aurelius\"]]],[1,\"blockquote\",[[0,[0],0,\"He who fears death will never do anything worthy of a man who is alive.  \"],[0,[2],2,\"~ Seneca\"]]],[3,\"ul\",[[[0,[],0,\"How have you integrated the knowledge of your own mortality into your life? Has this been a positive or negative experience?\"]],[[0,[],0,\"Do you fear death? If so, are you able to introspect deeper to understand what you truly fear? For example, perhaps you fear being forgotten by the world, or you fear the uncertainty of an afterlife.\"]]]],[1,\"h3\",[[0,[2],1,\"Week V — Focus on your sphere of control\"]]],[1,\"blockquote\",[[0,[0],0,\"The chief task in life is simply this: to identify and separate matters so that I can say clearly to myself which are externals not under my control, and which have to do with the choices I actually control. Where then do I look for good and evil? Not to uncontrollable externals, but within myself to the choices that are my own.  \"],[0,[2],2,\"~ Epictetus\"]]],[3,\"ul\",[[[0,[],0,\"Share a time when you\'ve managed to adjust your approach after realizing you were trying to \\\"over-control\\\" a situation, and how that benefited you.\"]],[[0,[],0,\"Sometimes being successful requires a \\\"leap of faith\\\" that perhaps you can control more than you thought possible. How can we embrace ambition without focusing on things outside our control? Or are these two ideas really in tension?\"]]]],[1,\"h3\",[[0,[2],1,\"Week VI — True Wealth\"]]],[1,\"blockquote\",[[0,[0],0,\"Wealth consists not in having great possessions, but in having few wants.  \"],[0,[2],2,\"~ Epictetus\"]]],[3,\"ul\",[[[0,[],0,\"Are there any physical possessions that you\'re particularly attached to? How if at all have these attachments limited your freedom or mental health?\"]],[[0,[],0,\"What are some techniques for limiting our true desires to only what we know will truly bring us fulfillment?\"],[1,[],0,0]]]]]}','<p><em>An experiment in community, philosophy and self-improvement</em></p><p>We’re living in a time of disconnection and isolation. And on top of that, powerful forces like Twitter\'s character limit and the 24-hour news cycle mean that our culture is often incredibly shallow — our conversations on important issues often lack emotional and intellectual depth.</p><p><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stoicism\">Stoic philosophy</a> offers a deep, rich and time-tested antidote to these ills.</p><p>A <strong>Stoic Circle</strong> is a small intentional community of 6-8 people that meets each week to discuss a single principle from the Stoic philosophers. We seek to apply the lessons of the Stoics into our own lives. Part group therapy, part philosophy discussion, part self-help circle, it’s an intentional community that strives to go beneath the surface to get at the deep emotional issues we face in our lives.</p><h2 id=\"values-inside-the-circle\"><strong>Values inside the Circle</strong></h2><p>When we enter the circle each week, we choose to embody the following values:</p><ul><li><strong>Self-improvement</strong> — We strive to improve ourselves. We actively encourage this mindset in those around us. We seek to avoid negative or unproductive thought patterns and recognize that growth is a never-ending game.</li><li><strong>Openness</strong> — We value honesty and transparency, and are willing to speak frankly about our own inner lives. We try to look deeply within ourselves in order to recognize, articulate and share our own insecurities, weaknesses and self-doubts, as well as our inner triumphs and victories over fear.</li></ul><h2 id=\"format-of-the-circle\"><strong>Format of the Circle</strong></h2><p>A Stoic Circle consists of a 1 hour meeting per week for 6 weeks. For now this will be on Zoom to facilitate social distancing.</p><p>Each week we will discuss a single short excerpt from the Stoic philosophers, and a few related prompts to provoke discussion. Here is the six week syllabus:</p><h3 id=\"week-i-avoiding-outrage\"><strong>Week I — Avoiding outrage</strong></h3><blockquote><em>Choose not to be harmed — and you won’t feel harmed. Don’t feel harmed — and you haven’t been.  <strong>~ Marcus Aurelius</strong></em></blockquote><ul><li>Have you observed any negative impacts in your life from the emotion of outrage?</li><li>Outrage is addictive. What habits or behaviors do you engage in that provoke your outrage? What are some techniques for avoiding this?</li></ul><h3 id=\"week-ii-self-discipline\"><strong>Week II — Self-discipline</strong></h3><blockquote><em>Be tolerant with others and strict with yourself.  <strong>~ Marcus Aurelius</strong></em></blockquote><ul><li>It\'s easy to look out at the world and cast judgement. Have you found yourself able to resist this urge? If so, have you found this to be beneficial?</li><li>Share a story of a time when you managed to stay disciplined towards a healthy intention you set, and how this improved your life.</li></ul><h3 id=\"week-iii-the-value-of-time\"><strong>Week III — The value of time</strong></h3><blockquote><em>People are frugal in guarding their personal property; but as soon as it comes to squandering time they are most wasteful of the one thing in which it is right to be stingy.  <strong>~ Seneca</strong></em></blockquote><ul><li>Are there areas of your life you\'re spending more time on than you think ideal? Do you suffer from any addictions or compulsions that eat away at your time but that you\'re unable to abstain from?</li><li>What approaches do you have for evaluating whether different activities are worth your time?</li></ul><h3 id=\"week-iv-facing-mortality\"><strong>Week IV — Facing mortality</strong></h3><blockquote><em>You could leave life right now. Let that determine what you do and say and think.  <strong>~ Marcus Aurelius</strong></em></blockquote><blockquote><em>He who fears death will never do anything worthy of a man who is alive.  <strong>~ Seneca</strong></em></blockquote><ul><li>How have you integrated the knowledge of your own mortality into your life? Has this been a positive or negative experience?</li><li>Do you fear death? If so, are you able to introspect deeper to understand what you truly fear? For example, perhaps you fear being forgotten by the world, or you fear the uncertainty of an afterlife.</li></ul><h3 id=\"week-v-focus-on-your-sphere-of-control\"><strong>Week V — Focus on your sphere of control</strong></h3><blockquote><em>The chief task in life is simply this: to identify and separate matters so that I can say clearly to myself which are externals not under my control, and which have to do with the choices I actually control. Where then do I look for good and evil? Not to uncontrollable externals, but within myself to the choices that are my own.  <strong>~ Epictetus</strong></em></blockquote><ul><li>Share a time when you\'ve managed to adjust your approach after realizing you were trying to \"over-control\" a situation, and how that benefited you.</li><li>Sometimes being successful requires a \"leap of faith\" that perhaps you can control more than you thought possible. How can we embrace ambition without focusing on things outside our control? Or are these two ideas really in tension?</li></ul><h3 id=\"week-vi-true-wealth\"><strong>Week VI — True Wealth</strong></h3><blockquote><em>Wealth consists not in having great possessions, but in having few wants.  <strong>~ Epictetus</strong></em></blockquote><ul><li>Are there any physical possessions that you\'re particularly attached to? How if at all have these attachments limited your freedom or mental health?</li><li>What are some techniques for limiting our true desires to only what we know will truly bring us fulfillment?<br></li></ul>','5f0b9f0a76e291001ef8b0c6','An experiment in community, philosophy and self-improvement\n\nWe’re living in a time of disconnection and isolation. And on top of that,\npowerful forces like Twitter\'s character limit and the 24-hour news cycle mean\nthat our culture is often incredibly shallow — our conversations on important\nissues often lack emotional and intellectual depth.\n\nStoic philosophy [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stoicism] offers a deep, rich\nand time-tested antidote to these ills.\n\nA Stoic Circle is a small intentional community of 6-8 people that meets each\nweek to discuss a single principle from the Stoic philosophers. We seek to apply\nthe lessons of the Stoics into our own lives. Part group therapy, part\nphilosophy discussion, part self-help circle, it’s an intentional community that\nstrives to go beneath the surface to get at the deep emotional issues we face in\nour lives.\n\nValues inside the Circle\nWhen we enter the circle each week, we choose to embody the following values:\n\n * Self-improvement — We strive to improve ourselves. We actively encourage this\n   mindset in those around us. We seek to avoid negative or unproductive thought\n   patterns and recognize that growth is a never-ending game.\n * Openness — We value honesty and transparency, and are willing to speak\n   frankly about our own inner lives. We try to look deeply within ourselves in\n   order to recognize, articulate and share our own insecurities, weaknesses and\n   self-doubts, as well as our inner triumphs and victories over fear.\n\nFormat of the Circle\nA Stoic Circle consists of a 1 hour meeting per week for 6 weeks. For now this\nwill be on Zoom to facilitate social distancing.\n\nEach week we will discuss a single short excerpt from the Stoic philosophers,\nand a few related prompts to provoke discussion. Here is the six week syllabus:\n\nWeek I — Avoiding outrage\n> Choose not to be harmed — and you won’t feel harmed. Don’t feel harmed — and you\nhaven’t been.~ Marcus Aurelius\n * Have you observed any negative impacts in your life from the emotion of\n   outrage?\n * Outrage is addictive. What habits or behaviors do you engage in that provoke\n   your outrage? What are some techniques for avoiding this?\n\nWeek II — Self-discipline\n> Be tolerant with others and strict with yourself.~ Marcus Aurelius\n * It\'s easy to look out at the world and cast judgement. Have you found\n   yourself able to resist this urge? If so, have you found this to be\n   beneficial?\n * Share a story of a time when you managed to stay disciplined towards a\n   healthy intention you set, and how this improved your life.\n\nWeek III — The value of time\n> People are frugal in guarding their personal property; but as soon as it comes\nto squandering time they are most wasteful of the one thing in which it is right\nto be stingy.~ Seneca\n * Are there areas of your life you\'re spending more time on than you think\n   ideal? Do you suffer from any addictions or compulsions that eat away at your\n   time but that you\'re unable to abstain from?\n * What approaches do you have for evaluating whether different activities are\n   worth your time?\n\nWeek IV — Facing mortality\n> You could leave life right now. Let that determine what you do and say and\nthink.~ Marcus Aurelius\n> He who fears death will never do anything worthy of a man who is alive.~ Seneca\n * How have you integrated the knowledge of your own mortality into your life?\n   Has this been a positive or negative experience?\n * Do you fear death? If so, are you able to introspect deeper to understand\n   what you truly fear? For example, perhaps you fear being forgotten by the\n   world, or you fear the uncertainty of an afterlife.\n\nWeek V — Focus on your sphere of control\n> The chief task in life is simply this: to identify and separate matters so that\nI can say clearly to myself which are externals not under my control, and which\nhave to do with the choices I actually control. Where then do I look for good\nand evil? Not to uncontrollable externals, but within myself to the choices that\nare my own.~ Epictetus\n * Share a time when you\'ve managed to adjust your approach after realizing you\n   were trying to \"over-control\" a situation, and how that benefited you.\n * Sometimes being successful requires a \"leap of faith\" that perhaps you can\n   control more than you thought possible. How can we embrace ambition without\n   focusing on things outside our control? Or are these two ideas really in\n   tension?\n\nWeek VI — True Wealth\n> Wealth consists not in having great possessions, but in having few wants.~\nEpictetus\n * Are there any physical possessions that you\'re particularly attached to? How\n   if at all have these attachments limited your freedom or mental health?\n * What are some techniques for limiting our true desires to only what we know\n   will truly bring us fulfillment?','https://s3.amazonaws.com/bucketeer-7bce7cd3-3552-4b4e-8681-9def67f16a7f/2020/07/marcus--1-.jpg',0,'published',NULL,'public','1','2020-07-12 23:38:50','1','2020-07-15 08:17:37','1','2020-07-10 23:39:00','1',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'post',0),('5f0ebcfff9cb25003b87c814','6e67fb19-470c-4be7-882b-8fb226bd540b','The Wikipedia Effect','the-wikipedia-effect','{\"version\":\"0.3.1\",\"atoms\":[],\"cards\":[],\"markups\":[[\"strong\"],[\"a\",[\"href\",\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Schadenfreude\"]],[\"a\",[\"href\",\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hygge\"]],[\"a\",[\"href\",\"/chopins-nocturnes/\"]],[\"em\"]],\"sections\":[[1,\"p\",[[0,[],0,\"A lot of things are deeply strange about having all of human knowledge available at our fingertips.\"]]],[1,\"p\",[[0,[],0,\"Our societies are still convulsing over the massive shocks this has had on our cultural and political systems. But much of the impact from the internet on our lives is felt not at the societal-scale, but much closer to home. This is the first post in a series I\'m planning, to explore about the intimate psychological effects caused by the internet.\"]]],[1,\"p\",[[0,[],0,\"Today\'s post is on a phenomenon I\'m calling \\\"The Wikipedia Effect\\\"\"]]],[1,\"blockquote\",[[0,[0],1,\"The Wikipedia Effect\"],[0,[],0,\" — The subtle sense of deflation and disillusionment felt after reading the Wikipedia article for a new concept.\"]]],[1,\"p\",[[0,[],0,\"The feeling may come from realizing that your new idea is not as novel as you thought. Or it may be because Wikipedia managed to break apart a work you found beautiful into its component parts in a way that is precisely correct yet wholly dissatisfying.\"]]],[1,\"p\",[[0,[],0,\"Like \"],[0,[1],1,\"schadenfreude\"],[0,[],0,\" or \"],[0,[2],1,\"hygge\"],[0,[],0,\", this emotion is complex to pin down. I\'ll try to illustrate it more clearly with a few examples.\"]]],[3,\"ul\",[[[0,[],0,\"I\'ve recently been very engrossed in listening to and attempting to play \"],[0,[3],0,\"Chopin\'s \"],[0,[4],2,\"Nocturnes\"],[0,[4],1,\".\"],[0,[],0,\" The Wikipedia article slices up their form into such a concise phrase that it left me feeling dumb. \\\"The nocturnes are generally set in ternary form (A–B–A), featuring a melancholy mood, and a clear melody floating over a left-hand accompaniment of arpeggios or broken chords. Repetitions of the main theme generally add increasingly ornate embellishments\\\" TODO: Drafting and explanation\"]],[[0,[],0,\"TODO: More examples\"]]]],[1,\"p\",[]]]}','<p>A lot of things are deeply strange about having all of human knowledge available at our fingertips.</p><p>Our societies are still convulsing over the massive shocks this has had on our cultural and political systems. But much of the impact from the internet on our lives is felt not at the societal-scale, but much closer to home. This is the first post in a series I\'m planning, to explore about the intimate psychological effects caused by the internet.</p><p>Today\'s post is on a phenomenon I\'m calling \"The Wikipedia Effect\"</p><blockquote><strong>The Wikipedia Effect</strong> — The subtle sense of deflation and disillusionment felt after reading the Wikipedia article for a new concept.</blockquote><p>The feeling may come from realizing that your new idea is not as novel as you thought. Or it may be because Wikipedia managed to break apart a work you found beautiful into its component parts in a way that is precisely correct yet wholly dissatisfying.</p><p>Like <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Schadenfreude\">schadenfreude</a> or <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hygge\">hygge</a>, this emotion is complex to pin down. I\'ll try to illustrate it more clearly with a few examples.</p><ul><li>I\'ve recently been very engrossed in listening to and attempting to play <a href=\"/chopins-nocturnes/\">Chopin\'s <em>Nocturnes</em></a><em>.</em> The Wikipedia article slices up their form into such a concise phrase that it left me feeling dumb. \"The nocturnes are generally set in ternary form (A–B–A), featuring a melancholy mood, and a clear melody floating over a left-hand accompaniment of arpeggios or broken chords. Repetitions of the main theme generally add increasingly ornate embellishments\" TODO: Drafting and explanation</li><li>TODO: More examples</li></ul>','5f0ebcfff9cb25003b87c814','A lot of things are deeply strange about having all of human knowledge available\nat our fingertips.\n\nOur societies are still convulsing over the massive shocks this has had on our\ncultural and political systems. But much of the impact from the internet on our\nlives is felt not at the societal-scale, but much closer to home. This is the\nfirst post in a series I\'m planning, to explore about the intimate psychological\neffects caused by the internet.\n\nToday\'s post is on a phenomenon I\'m calling \"The Wikipedia Effect\"\n\n> The Wikipedia Effect — The subtle sense of deflation and disillusionment felt\nafter reading the Wikipedia article for a new concept.\nThe feeling may come from realizing that your new idea is not as novel as you\nthought. Or it may be because Wikipedia managed to break apart a work you found\nbeautiful into its component parts in a way that is precisely correct yet wholly\ndissatisfying.\n\nLike schadenfreude [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Schadenfreude] or hygge\n[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hygge], this emotion is complex to pin down. I\'ll\ntry to illustrate it more clearly with a few examples.\n\n * I\'ve recently been very engrossed in listening to and attempting to play \n   Chopin\'s Nocturnes [/chopins-nocturnes/]. The Wikipedia article slices up\n   their form into such a concise phrase that it left me feeling dumb. \"The\n   nocturnes are generally set in ternary form (A–B–A), featuring a melancholy\n   mood, and a clear melody floating over a left-hand accompaniment of arpeggios\n   or broken chords. Repetitions of the main theme generally add increasingly\n   ornate embellishments\" TODO: Drafting and explanation\n * TODO: More examples',NULL,0,'draft',NULL,'public','1','2020-07-15 08:23:27','1','2020-07-15 08:48:24','1',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'post',0);
